metadata.name: The Face We Had #251
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: Scattered Pathways #400
metadata.description:
"Scattered Pathways" studies pathfinding on a grid. I enjoy watching the sketch find and fill the available spaces. I hope you enjoy this one too!

Royalties Splits:
50% Donation to minter

Features:
Two different sizes: 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
@liamegan1/fxhash-helpers
@altesc/stdio

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

metadata.name: Yaff #350
metadata.description:
I used this collection to teach my daughter a little bit about generative art. We enjoyed working on it so much that I wanted to share it so she could see it out in the wild.

All primary sales proceeds will be donated to bellyful, a local charity supporting new parents.

Keyboard shortcuts:
"s" - Save hi-res image
"p" - Start/stop animation
"o" - Show/hide particle tails (when animating)

metadata.name: Mid Morning Doodles #107
metadata.description:
This project is part of several experiments combining individual hand-drawn "squiggles" and turning them into something unexpected. This project is an evolution of a few of my previous projects, such as "Teal Iron Elaphrosaurus," "Mercury Phosphorus Lily," "Late Night Sketches," and "Late Night Sketches II."

The assets used in this project were hand-drawn with markers, pens, and ink. I will sit down for several hours and draw pages of elements in one of my sketchbooks. I then scan the drawings and separate them into transparent png files in Photoshop. Then the p5.js sketch takes those images and places them according to a grid according to the project features.

There are 483 individually drawn "squiggles" for the p5.js sketch to pick from to build up the final image. Please be patient (the 'Done rendering!' comment in the browser console is all-clear), as some renders may take longer than others. I made all the drawings for this project from December 2022 through the project creation date. This project is tested in Google Chrome using the fx(stdio) framework.

I hope you enjoy these as much as I do making them! 

I have set secondary royalty to split 50/50 between the minter and myself. 

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: print size @ 2,200px x 2,750px (4:5 ratio)

You can find more at https://linktr.ee/natenolting.

metadata.name: regularity #39
metadata.description: This generative NFT created with three.js is an animated geometric masterpiece. The animation is a mesmerizing display of intricate shapes and patterns that move and morph in hypnotic ways, creating a stunning visual experience for the viewer. The geometry is complex and detailed, with an almost fractal-like quality to it, adding to the sense of depth and immersion in the artwork.
